##Chinese students face a choice: bear the economic loss or change their study plan?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

The spread of the new coronavirus has affected Chinese students already studying abroad, and Chinese students preparing to apply to study abroad this year are also facing changes to their exam plans, even if they pass the exam and apply for admission, whether they can make it to destinations such as Australia this summer is also up in the air

By Wang Xiaofeng, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Hao Zhou

During the Spring Festival in 2020, the spread of COVID-19 caught some Chinese students returning home for the Lunar New Year Unawares, because some countries impose temporary restrictions on people who have traveled to China in the past, especially in Wuhan, Hubei Province, Australia and the United States are becoming a dilemma for Chinese students.

Chinese students restricted from returning to Australia for classes after Spring Festival

Australia is in the Southern Hemisphere, and most Chinese students return to Australia in mid-february for the Chinese New Year, which falls during the summer holiday. This Spring Festival, the practice was interrupted by a sudden outbreak of the disease.

China Standard Time, Australian Prime Minister Morrison said at a press conference on Feb. 1 that Australia will ban all people who arrive in Australia from China after Feb. 1, with the exception of Australian citizens, permanent residents and their immediate family members and crew. Chinese who have entered Australia will be quarantined for 14 days. On the day of Morrison's announcement, Qantas also said it would suspend flights between Beijing and Shanghai to and from Australia between February 9 and March 29.

The travel ban is understood to be in effect for two weeks, with an assessment to be made in two weeks. Many Chinese students returning to China for the Chinese New Year are worried because the university starts in mid to late February and if they miss two weeks, they can not register until the next semester, will have to wait until next school year. For those Chinese students who have graduated and are returning home for the Spring Festival, their plans to apply for work visas in Australia will be affected and there is a high risk that they will not be able to apply for jobs in Australia.

The Australian restrictions have caused a strong reaction among Chinese students recently. Some students had planned to return to Australian schools after the Lantern Festival, but Australia's new decision and the airlines canceled the latest flights, there was no chance of them changing their tickets, and some complained about the decision.

The wechat group of Australian students is full of anxiety

On Jan. 31, the World Health Organization classified the COVID-19 outbreak in China as a "public health emergency of international concern, " but the organization's director general also emphasized that, do not support or even oppose the travel or trade ban imposed on China by other countries. However, the United States, Australia, Singapore, Russia and other countries have recently imposed temporary travel bans on Chinese travelers due to concerns about the spread of the disease.

Some Chinese students who arrived in Australia on the same day were denied entry and arranged to leave after Morrison's ban was issued at entry points in major Australian cities.

Wang, who is studying in Australia, told Caijing that one of his classmates was on a Feb. 1 flight back to Australia, but was barred from entering the country after arriving at an Australian airport, and was later arranged to fly back to China. There are also Chinese students who have come to Australia through third party connections, such as Ai Si Li, who is about to go to University of New South Wales to study business analysis as a graduate student, told CAIJING, a friend of hers arrived in Australia on Feb. 1, en route from South Korea.

Li Aisi, from Taiyuan, Shanxi Province, is not so lucky herself. She is a freshman at an Australian university for the 2020"fall semester" (southern hemisphere fall starts in February) . These days she and her mother are worried about whether they will be forced to suspend and quarantine when they arrive in Australia. They had been scheduled to fly to Australia on a HNA flight on Feb. 10, but they received word of the cancellation shortly after Morrison announced the ban. Li Aisi in a group of more than 150 people studying abroad, about half of them returned home for the Spring Festival, and now are anxious about how to return to school in Australia.

Lu Bin, who has a master's degree in law from the University of Sydney, is waiting for an update at his home in Changsha, Hunan Province. Her classmates tried to board a connecting flight to Australia from Hong Kong, but were not allowed to board. "There are more than 100 Chinese students majoring in this subject in our university, and 80 percent of them go home for Chinese New Year, and now they can't go back home, " Rubin told Caijing.

Unable to return to Australia to continue their studies, will bring foreign students a considerable financial loss. Vivibear, a graduate student in International Journalism at University of Melbourne who lives in Zhengzhou, Henan Province, had planned to return to Australia on Feb. 27, and 90 percent of her classmates returned to China during the Lunar New Year holiday. Now, because of the policy change, Vivibear told Caijing, she is hesitant to pay the tuition for the upcoming "fall semester" by the Feb. 14 deadline, or miss a whole semester if she doesn't. Many Chinese students pay rent in advance, and if they don't go back, the rent will be wiped out.

The Chinese students are waiting for Australian universities to come up with a policy, and the Australian Home Office has advised them to contact the university for an extension and, if necessary, communicate with the university about online teaching. Chinese students argue that the recommendations are a palliative and would be meaningless if they were taught online for a full semester.

It is understood that some Australian universities have introduced measures to try to reduce the impact of the new immigration restrictions on Chinese students. The University of New South Wales said in an e mail to students that Chinese students could delay registration until Feb. 28 at the latest, and that online teaching support would be available for the first two weeks, late-registered Chinese students can only take two courses instead of three during the "fall semester" because of the impact of delayed enrollment on the teaching schedule. The President of the University of Sydney also sent a letter reassuring Chinese students that the university is studying how to continue its studies outside the university and looking forward to the early return of Chinese students.

Overseas students need to consider more variables

Australia is an important destination country for Chinese students. A record number of Chinese students chose to study in Australia in 2018, rising 17 percent to 173,000 from 147,000 in 2017, the highest number of foreign students in Australia, according to Australian official data. More than 37 per cent of foreign students in Australia are from China, according to separate figures.

The Australian independent research centre has analysed seven universities in the country that rely heavily on Chinese students for income growth. If the number of Chinese students going to Australia Falls, the schools will be in financial trouble.

It is understood that some Chinese students have launched an online petition to urge the Australian government to allow them to enter the country as soon as possible to study. China is the largest overseas market for Australia's education industry, they said, and any delay in study due to non-entry will affect Chinese students'confidence in choosing Australia as a study destination.

CAIJING reporter asked the Australian Embassy in China, whether Australia will extend the travel ban? Embassy staff said the issue will be answered by Canberra. So far, neither the Australian Ministry of Foreign Affairs nor the Ministry of Education has responded positively to CAIJING's questions.

Chinese students studying in the United States are less affected than those in Australia. Because most American schools open in January. Some students also have trouble returning to China for the Spring Festival. Li Lan, who was studying at New York University, returned to the United States ahead of the Lunar New Year. She was worried about border control when she saw the epidemic spreading. She returned to the United States ahead of schedule on Jan. 26. "after the policy was announced, ticket prices soared, and one of my classmates had to make multiple connections to get back to the United States before the ban went into effect, " Li told CAIJING.

The spread of the disease in the United States is limited, but Ms. Li's Long Island apartment in New York is filled with Chinese students who come and go wearing face masks because it is not clear who is from the affected city and whether it is contagious. Li Lan lived in the apartment wechat group has spread, parents from Wuhan to live here, which made many people nervous for a time.

According to US sources, a recent visitor to the Arizona State University campus (Asu) was diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia and treated under isolation, some of the university's overseas students also confirmed the news to CAIJING reporters. This caused a certain amount of panic in the Arizona State University, with some students calling for the school to be suspended. "CAIJING" reporter learned that the school has a professor to let students temporarily holiday. In response to the US government's request for self-isolation of travellers from Wuhan, China, a Chinese student returning from Wuhan on January 9 with a pre-return fever is now in self-isolation, awaiting confirmation of new coronary pneumonia.

The spread of the outbreak and its ripple effects are also starting to affect the exam plans for Chinese students applying to study abroad this year. The Educational Testing Service (Ets) has issued a notice to cancel all toefl and GRE General tests for February 2020 in mainland China with immediate effect. The UK's IELTS official Weibo also announced the cancellation of all ielts tests on January 31 and February 2020 in mainland China.

After the announcement of the test changes, many foreign English teaching platforms have released news to help students cope with the changes. Some students are worried about whether the English language test for studying abroad in March or April will also be canceled. Regarding the possibility, a practitioner from a well-known online English language teaching platform told CAIJING that ETS should consider it as appropriate, cancelling too many exams will put pressure on the arrangements for the rest of the year and affect university applications by some Chinese students at the end of the year.

According to Caijing, students have been told to change the venue of exams for subjects that require an exit exam, as Singapore and other neighboring countries temporarily restrict Chinese residents from entering the country. Places such as Cambodia and Thailand, which have not yet fully restricted the entry of Chinese residents, have become the new choices for Chinese students to take overseas exams in March. Whether or not these replacements are possible remains to be seen, depending on the progress made in the prevention and control of the disease.

(the names Wang, Li Aisi, Lu bin, Vivibear and Li Lan are all pseudonyms.)
